@Misc{SSW:Perera,
  Title                    = {City Data Fusion: Sensor Data Fusion in the Internet of Things},

  Author                   = {Wang, Meisong and Perera, Charith and Jayaraman, Prem Prakash and Zhang, Miranda and Strazdins, Peter and Ranjan, Rajiv},
  Year                     = {2015},

  Abstract                 = {This article introduces the concept of IoT and presents in detail ten different parameters that govern their sensor data fusion evaluation framework. The main goal is to examine and survey different sensor data fusion research efforts based on our evaluation framework. 

The concept of Sensor Data Fusion is described as well its relevance in the IoT. It can be described as a data processing technique that associates, combines, aggregates, and integrates data fromdifferentsources. The article mentions three key operations of sensor data fusion: complementary (creating a large picture from small bits of information), redundant (integrate sensors for improved accuracy), and cooperative (combine sensors to produce new knowledge). The ultimate goal of sensor data fusion is to under- stand the environment and act accordingly. 

My thesis will be focused on the complementary and redundant aspects of sensor data fusion with the future option of cooperative through links in the semantic web. 

There is very little interest in the raw sensor data. The data that is of significant interest is information about interesting events that are happening in the specific area.

The ten parameters are: Middleware Architecture Type, Context-awareness, Semantic Interaction, Dynamic Configuration, Fusion Complexity, Actuation Management, Type of Processing, Cross Domain Portability, Implementation and Performance Evaluation.

Using middleware in semantic sensor network architectures is about creating an abstraction level, which results in a degraded performance over applications that directly consult the sensors. However, middleware systems can bundle important functionalities together to be reused in many applications. The article identifies developing middleware as the right way to address the needs of IoT applications.

Connecting sensors to the semantic web (Semantic Sensor Web) is mentioned as an important step to increase the retrievability of sensor data.

The article describes the potential of IoT and evaluates a number of 'state of the art' examples of Sensor Data Fusion. Table 1: Taxonomy of Sensor Data Fusion Research Efforts contains a taxonomy of a couple dozen researches.},
